article.headline: Houston hits 15 free throws down stretch
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) --The Indiana Fever couldn't stop Tina Thompson, and
they kept sending the Houston Comets to the free-throw line.

Thompson had 31 points and 10 rebounds to lead the Comets to a
62-54 win over the slumping Fever on Saturday.

Sheryl Swoopes added 12 points for the Comets, who did not make
a field goal in the final 10:52, but sank 15 of 20 free throws down
the stretch.

Thompson finished 8-for-17 from the field and 11-for-14 from the
line. She was 4-for-4 from 3-point range.

"Surprisingly they were giving me a lot of open shots and those
just don't come that easily," Thompson said.

Tamika Catchings had 18 points and 13 rebounds for the Fever,
losers of six straight games. Catchings struggled, going 6-for-24
from the field. Natalie Williams added 13 points and nine rebounds.

The Fever (12-14) got within four points with 36 seconds to go,
but the Comets won their fifth straight game at the line. Houston
made 20-of-28 free throws.

The Comets led 31-25 at the break behind Thompson's 18 points.

In the second half, the Fever (12-15) got within 31-29 on a jump
shot by Catchings. Houston responded with a 12-5 run to take a
43-34 lead with 12:35 left.

The Comets are coming off a 80-55 win Tuesday over the
second-place Seattle Storm. Houston sits in fifth place in the
Western Conference.

"I thought this, along with the game we won on Tuesday, were
must-win games and we got them," Swoopes said. "Not just to give
us momentum going into the break, but to get us in a good position
to make a run for the playoffs."

The WNBA takes a monthlong break in August for the Olympics.

Indiana shot 27 percent, but out-rebounded Houston 36-34 and
forced the Comets into 15 turnovers.

"We haven't been shooting well the last six games, and today
they just played really good defense," Catchings said. "We just
couldn't finish."
